1
00:00:00,830 --> 00:00:02,210
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,850 --> 00:00:04,230
Got a free day.

3
00:00:05,010 --> 00:00:06,690
Filming on February 23rd.

4
00:00:06,990 --> 00:00:08,390
Happy Defender of the Fatherland Day to all the guys.

5
00:00:09,870 --> 00:00:19,610
So, here's the schematic of the improved pulse amplifier for the signal generator.

6
00:00:20,070 --> 00:00:23,390
My previous schematic, shown here.

7
00:00:24,090 --> 00:00:26,010
A video about it is on my channel.

8
00:00:27,910 --> 00:00:30,650
Why did I decide to improve this schematic?

9
00:00:31,410 --> 00:00:36,870
The thing is, the schematic itself is very interesting and useful.

10
00:00:36,990 --> 00:00:46,210
But it has a common point with the inductor that drives the coil.

11
00:00:47,550 --> 00:00:55,890
If the coil is the grenade type, no problem — everything's fine.

12
00:00:56,150 --> 00:01:15,630
But if you put a Tesla here, then at some operating modes, if you hit the effect — for example, tune the frequency and duty cycle so you hit a harmonic from wave resonance, you'll see interesting effects.

13
00:01:15,630 --> 00:01:21,550
Interesting effects.

14
00:01:22,530 --> 00:01:34,510
And with these interesting effects, if the supply for this switch is around 50 V, you can say goodbye to your lab signal generator.

15
00:01:35,510 --> 00:01:42,870
In general, our experiments are pretty dangerous for oscilloscopes and signal generators.

16
00:01:44,010 --> 00:01:56,010
So, to avoid that — the gear is expensive — I made an upgrade of this schematic, which is shown here.

17
00:01:58,770 --> 00:02:01,150
Let's look at the schematic in more detail.

18
00:02:02,150 --> 00:02:07,530
The chip lineup is the same — TC4093BP.

19
00:02:09,030 --> 00:02:18,190
This chip mediates between the lab signal generator and the TC4420 driver.

20
00:02:18,930 --> 00:02:29,370
If you need this circuit to run continuously, this mediator can be removed.

21
00:02:29,370 --> 00:02:44,310
Or if you have a really good lab signal generator that can output not just pulses with set frequency and duty cycle but also chop those pulses

22
00:02:44,310 --> 00:02:49,950
into bursts — then you won't need this chip.

23
00:02:50,070 --> 00:03:01,490
You can feed the signal directly from such a lab generator to pin 2 of the driver that controls the transistor, through the isolation transformer.

24
00:03:02,950 --> 00:03:06,310
And that simplifies the schematic.

25
00:03:07,210 --> 00:03:23,290
But I still leave this chip in, because in practice it happens that the lab signal generator gets disconnected — say, this node is moved somewhere else so

26
00:03:23,530 --> 00:03:27,130
the Tesla doesn't affect nearby devices.

27
00:03:28,110 --> 00:03:43,010
And you can see there are three inputs — one of them common, and two inputs connected to pins 1 and 2 of the TC4093 chip.

28
00:03:44,670 --> 00:03:50,670
The chip's logic element is a Schmitt trigger.

29
00:03:51,890 --> 00:04:03,070
Its input is a 2-input AND, and then the signal gets inverted after the Schmitt trigger.

30
00:04:03,430 --> 00:04:25,330
So if we use outputs 1 and 2 separately, we can do something really interesting — when one generator (say, on logic gates) sets a frequency for us of, say, 100 kHz, we feed it

31
00:04:25,330 --> 00:04:35,910
to one input of the chip, and the second generator on logic gates produces a frequency of, say, 1 kHz.

32
00:04:36,510 --> 00:04:47,590
And with this logic, the chip will make bursts at 1 kHz, and the filling of those bursts will be at 100 kHz.

33
00:04:47,590 --> 00:05:04,170
And if the signal generators controlling this chip also have duty cycle adjustment — say on the low-frequency generator — then the chip puts all those parameters into burst form

34
00:05:04,170 --> 00:05:08,010
and sends them to the driver.

35
00:05:09,070 --> 00:05:11,170
Really handy.

36
00:05:13,210 --> 00:05:34,190
If you need this circuit to produce a continuous signal, you tie inputs 1 and 2 together at this terminal, and the chip transmits the signal from the controlling generator

37
00:05:34,190 --> 00:05:35,530
straight through to the driver.

38
00:05:36,430 --> 00:05:46,470
You can see the second inversion is done to return the signal to its original form at the input, and the control goes to pin 2 of the driver.

39
00:05:48,870 --> 00:05:57,490
You can also note that this schematic uses a principle where the common wire is only on the control side.

40
00:05:57,990 --> 00:06:09,670
That is — the driving generator (or lab generator), the mediator chip, the driver, the DC-DC converter, and the power source are tied together.

41
00:06:10,270 --> 00:06:13,630
This whole part has a common wire.

42
00:06:14,310 --> 00:06:22,450
The rest is fully galvanically isolated from the control block.

43
00:06:23,050 --> 00:06:33,220
This way, with transformer isolation, we prevent any galvanic connection of the control block with the power side.

44
00:06:35,990 --> 00:06:43,470
Let's look at this node that galvanically isolates the control block and the power side in more detail.

45
00:06:44,210 --> 00:06:48,870
You can see the driver works into an inductive load.

46
00:06:50,150 --> 00:06:59,150
To prevent the driver from being shorted to the common wire, a 1 µF 50 V capacitor is in series.

47
00:06:59,970 --> 00:07:04,410
This cap also removes the DC component from the signal.

48
00:07:05,410 --> 00:07:15,810
And a 12.4 Ω resistor in series limits the current through the primary winding.

49
00:07:16,650 --> 00:07:21,610
Next, the signal from the primary is picked up by the secondary.

50
00:07:22,170 --> 00:07:28,290
Through another 1 µF capacitor it feeds the transistor gate.

51
00:07:28,290 --> 00:07:45,630
But here you see some support circuitry that ultimately shapes the signal, gives it a square shape, and limits the maximum voltage so the transistor doesn't break down.

52
00:07:46,610 --> 00:07:53,510
To remove the negative component, there's this UF 4005 diode.

53
00:07:55,490 --> 00:08:05,770
Instead of this diode, you can use other fast diodes — for example, SF, HER and similar.

54
00:08:07,030 --> 00:08:12,410
Next we see a 1 kΩ gate discharge resistor.

55
00:08:12,910 --> 00:08:20,410
And it's mandatory in this circuit to use counter-connected 15 V zener diodes.

56
00:08:20,410 --> 00:08:33,330
These zeners cut off the spikes that can form on the secondary when the frequency changes, protecting the transistor gate from breakdown.

57
00:08:34,910 --> 00:08:45,210
For the isolation transformer core that drives the power switch gate, I used this ferrite ring.

58
00:08:46,150 --> 00:08:51,050
I outlined it here so the actual dimensions are clear.

59
00:08:51,590 --> 00:09:01,910
The inner hole diameter is 10 mm, outer diameter 20 mm, and ring width is 10 mm.

60
00:09:02,590 --> 00:09:04,870
Its permeability is mark 2000.

61
00:09:06,250 --> 00:09:18,950
This ring is enough to drive pretty powerful switches, and you can use not just IRF-series transistors in this circuit.

62
00:09:19,830 --> 00:09:27,130
If available, I'd recommend swapping IRF840 for IRF510.

63
00:09:27,590 --> 00:09:32,990
This transistor has only 15 pF gate capacitance.

64
00:09:32,990 --> 00:09:42,280
And the IRF510, with proper gate-drive wiring, can work at frequencies up to 30 MHz.

65
00:09:46,470 --> 00:09:50,410
I added a terminal block to this circuit.

66
00:09:51,270 --> 00:10:02,690
I did this so I could switch between different connection schemes of the transistor leads and the power source.

67
00:10:03,690 --> 00:10:22,630
For example, if we connect the minus of the switch's power supply with its source on this terminal block, we get the standard schematic where minus goes directly to the transistor source, and the drain

68
00:10:22,630 --> 00:10:34,050
is loaded with the inductive load — which in Tesla circuits is the primary winding.

69
00:10:34,770 --> 00:10:52,770
If, however, we connect the drain with the plus of the power supply on this terminal block, we get circuit variant 2 — inductor inclusion where the minus of the supply connects to the Tesla coil's inductor,

70
00:10:52,770 --> 00:11:01,710
and the other free end of the inductor connects to the source of this switch.

71
00:11:02,070 --> 00:11:13,330
I want to point out right away that these two circuits behave totally differently when working with the Tesla coil and show different effects.

72
00:11:14,550 --> 00:11:20,350
Few people know about this, and this circuit is the one most often used.

73
00:11:20,350 --> 00:11:21,010
Why?

74
00:11:21,270 --> 00:11:34,780
Because it's always convenient to put a driver, no need for an isolation transformer, and the load is in the drain circuit of the power switch.

75
00:11:36,770 --> 00:11:44,670
And a lot of schematics that some inventors share just show, say, a switch.

76
00:11:44,670 --> 00:11:51,630
But often this specific control circuit may be the one being used.

77
00:11:52,910 --> 00:11:55,990
These two circuits work absolutely differently.

78
00:11:56,310 --> 00:12:00,570
And the phenomena that happen on the Tesla coil are different.

79
00:12:01,510 --> 00:12:05,670
That's a tip for future experimenters.

80
00:12:05,670 --> 00:12:22,030
By the way, I want to mention that all the interesting effects in Tesla coils — and in general in the free-energy generator systems we assemble — only show up when three frequencies operate in the system.

81
00:12:22,030 --> 00:12:22,630
In the system.

82
00:12:23,530 --> 00:12:39,450
Say, for example, the frequency inside a burst, the burst repetition frequency, and a third frequency that forms in, say, the Tesla coil.

83
00:12:40,830 --> 00:12:44,010
Free oscillations, frequency beats.

84
00:12:44,690 --> 00:12:50,570
You can only see the interesting effects with the interaction of three frequencies.

85
00:12:51,450 --> 00:12:58,770
If we just feed one frequency, or even two — we won't get anything interesting.

86
00:13:00,010 --> 00:13:16,110
As a power source for the power switch load in this circuit, you can use a battery, or an inverter connected to a battery — the latter is preferable for raising the supply voltage.

87
00:13:16,710 --> 00:13:25,210
And less preferable is when we power this circuit from a lab power source.

88
00:13:25,210 --> 00:13:31,270
It's convenient, sure — for me there's regulation from zero to 300 V.

89
00:13:32,270 --> 00:13:38,570
But with this kind of connection to the mains, you can't tune the system.

90
00:13:39,550 --> 00:13:46,330
The effects show up in most cases when we have isolation from the mains.

91
00:13:46,930 --> 00:14:06,890
And even with the filter shown here on the schematic, you can still notice during operation — if you touch the switch's heat sink, you'll feel 50 Hz.

92
00:14:06,890 --> 00:14:12,690
You can feel it, despite the filter.

93
00:14:12,690 --> 00:14:16,850
And that introduces its own distortions to the system.

94
00:14:17,850 --> 00:14:35,670
So for precise tuning, especially when working with Tesla coils, I recommend using power from separate supplies that don't pull their energy from the mains.

95
00:14:36,670 --> 00:14:39,210
Let's look at this filter.

96
00:14:39,850 --> 00:14:42,670
It's shown on the board.

97
00:14:44,650 --> 00:15:00,890
These inductive filters can be salvaged from old TVs, old power supplies, or wound on yellow rings at home.

98
00:15:01,010 --> 00:15:05,350
That is, two windings — take two wires and wind them in parallel.

99
00:15:06,030 --> 00:15:08,570
You'll get the equivalent of this filter.

100
00:15:09,390 --> 00:15:13,750
The first cap value is 2 µF.

101
00:15:14,210 --> 00:15:20,310
Next, the filter itself, then another cap, 0.68 µF.

102
00:15:20,310 --> 00:15:26,530
Then the main reservoir cap, shown as 230 µF.

103
00:15:27,410 --> 00:15:30,530
The values can be quite different.

104
00:15:31,170 --> 00:15:36,510
The main thing is the voltage was 400 V because we feed up to 300 V here.

105
00:15:37,510 --> 00:15:44,010
In this case the caps are 200 V — I put them in series, and the capacitance halves.

106
00:15:44,010 --> 00:15:53,470
And the filter cap after the electrolytics is 28 nF.

107
00:15:54,150 --> 00:15:59,910
The caps were rated 2000 V — overkill, but they fit dimension-wise.

108
00:16:00,550 --> 00:16:05,230
Nothing complicated in this filter — assembles fast enough.

109
00:16:07,590 --> 00:16:18,410
Here on my experienced enclosure I've ended up with the latest circuit implementation.

110
00:16:18,750 --> 00:16:21,790
You can see previous holes from earlier work.

111
00:16:23,290 --> 00:16:26,030
Mounted the power switch on the heat sink.

112
00:16:27,990 --> 00:16:31,650
Mounted the terminal block carrier.

113
00:16:32,370 --> 00:16:41,430
And drilled holes for the wires to run per the wiring scheme.

114
00:16:44,250 --> 00:16:58,930
And here's the circuit that connects to the lab signal generator and drives the power switch.

115
00:16:58,930 --> 00:17:04,310
See what the isolation control transformer looks like.

116
00:17:05,150 --> 00:17:06,890
Wound with two wires at once.

117
00:17:08,070 --> 00:17:13,410
Primary and secondary turn count is the same — 11 turns.

118
00:17:14,190 --> 00:17:34,970
If we use a voltage stabilizer at the input — namely the LM2596 DC-DC converter — we can set the voltage point and without unwinding turns, set the desired voltage on the transistor gate.

119
00:17:34,970 --> 00:17:38,870
Set the desired voltage on the gate.

120
00:17:39,030 --> 00:17:41,150
So you can correct it that way.

121
00:17:42,790 --> 00:17:49,530
There's a certain prejudice people have about pulse transformers.

122
00:17:49,530 --> 00:17:52,350
But I'll tell you, it's a really good thing.

123
00:17:52,490 --> 00:18:00,510
If you learn to tune it, you can even forget about power switch drivers.

124
00:18:00,950 --> 00:18:02,870
Awesome harmonic isolation.

125
00:18:04,150 --> 00:18:06,730
This ferrite works.

126
00:18:07,030 --> 00:18:09,750
I tested it above 2 MHz.

127
00:18:10,390 --> 00:18:14,010
I'll show the signal from it later on the oscilloscope.

128
00:18:14,010 --> 00:18:19,850
And you can see this part — the little terminal block shown here.

129
00:18:20,150 --> 00:18:23,490
This is the TC4093 chip.

130
00:18:24,010 --> 00:18:37,390
And I want to point out that the TC4420 driver has a heat sink that I soldered to the board with two little wires.

131
00:18:38,510 --> 00:18:41,170
Under the heat sink we have thermal paste.

132
00:18:41,170 --> 00:18:43,070
What's the point?

133
00:18:44,030 --> 00:18:51,410
These drivers aren't developed by the manufacturer for these high frequencies at all.

134
00:18:51,570 --> 00:19:00,230
And this circuit can be used freely up to 2.5 MHz — maybe even higher.

135
00:19:00,670 --> 00:19:02,430
Because the transistors allow it.

136
00:19:03,130 --> 00:19:06,950
And the chip itself can work at these frequencies.

137
00:19:06,950 --> 00:19:17,350
The driver itself starts heating up when the frequency approaches the 1.6–1.7 MHz range.

138
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:22,340
The heating becomes noticeable — about 50 degrees.

139
00:19:23,110 --> 00:19:25,330
But I still added a heat sink.

140
00:19:25,570 --> 00:19:29,790
The heat sink is from cable clamps.

141
00:19:30,550 --> 00:19:36,770
You can buy them, and they fit very nicely on the surface of these chips.

142
00:19:37,930 --> 00:19:43,070
And basically, nothing super-complex here.

143
00:19:44,310 --> 00:19:51,450
You can see I raised the zener diodes up because in experiments anything can happen.

144
00:19:51,590 --> 00:19:57,150
If the power switch blows, the zener pair may blow.

145
00:19:57,310 --> 00:20:06,930
So to not disassemble the whole circuit, just snip the wires with little pieces and solder in new zeners here.

146
00:20:06,950 --> 00:20:09,170
And the circuit's working again.

147
00:20:09,750 --> 00:20:18,890
When the switch blows, nothing happens to the driver, the transformer, much less the control block.

148
00:20:19,750 --> 00:20:21,690
The circuit is reliably isolated.

149
00:20:25,300 --> 00:20:27,240
Assembled the circuit for demonstration.

150
00:20:27,660 --> 00:20:31,080
Now I'll show the circuit's frequency capabilities.

151
00:20:34,880 --> 00:20:42,680
The oscilloscope probe will be on the secondary winding output now.

152
00:20:43,220 --> 00:20:45,780
The rest of the circuit is disconnected.

153
00:20:46,480 --> 00:20:53,860
I'll show the signal shape so it doesn't scare you, while all this isn't there.

154
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:58,740
We'll start specifically at 1 kHz.

155
00:21:01,900 --> 00:21:04,620
So, power applied to the circuit.

156
00:21:07,740 --> 00:21:08,520
There you see.

157
00:21:10,840 --> 00:21:13,280
Now I'll enlarge the screen.

158
00:21:17,400 --> 00:21:23,540
So — pulse repetition frequency is 1 kHz.

159
00:21:24,420 --> 00:21:27,180
Remember, the secondary isn't connected anywhere.

160
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:29,880
And I start gradually increasing the frequency.

161
00:21:29,880 --> 00:21:35,440
1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

162
00:21:37,800 --> 00:21:47,000
And you can also observe the max amplitude of the positive and negative half-periods.

163
00:21:47,840 --> 00:21:50,380
The sweep is now 5 V per division.

164
00:21:51,720 --> 00:21:56,360
5 kHz, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10.

165
00:21:56,520 --> 00:21:58,100
Look how the signal changes.

166
00:21:59,880 --> 00:22:08,320
I'm showing these frequencies so you understand one important point.

167
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:12,480
This ferrite has a minimum operating frequency.

168
00:22:13,660 --> 00:22:28,220
If you want to make a circuit that should work at frequencies under 15 kHz, you should use a ferrite with a lower permeability mark.

169
00:22:28,220 --> 00:22:34,460
Not 2000 — go lower in permeability so it can work at low frequencies.

170
00:22:35,260 --> 00:22:38,960
This 2000 ferrite behaves well.

171
00:22:39,080 --> 00:22:46,180
Now I bring the frequency up to 15 kHz.

172
00:22:47,140 --> 00:22:52,900
And you see the signals taking a more square shape.

173
00:22:54,240 --> 00:23:02,160
And from 20 kHz on, this ferrite can work stably.

174
00:23:03,100 --> 00:23:05,900
Now let's raise the frequency faster.

175
00:23:06,900 --> 00:23:12,900
Frequency 70 — well, let's say 50 kHz.

176
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:20,880
The signal plateau is already nice — it's starting to form.

177
00:23:20,880 --> 00:23:22,760
Now 100 kHz.

178
00:23:24,880 --> 00:23:29,460
A nice signal shape.

179
00:23:30,040 --> 00:23:37,240
By the way, note the rising edge — we'll look more at it later.

180
00:23:37,880 --> 00:23:40,200
Now I'll change the frequency right away.

181
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:43,640
Now 600 kHz.

182
00:23:46,880 --> 00:23:49,000
Here the frequency is 1 MHz.

183
00:23:54,840 --> 00:24:02,480
Add — 1.5 MHz signal like this.

184
00:24:02,900 --> 00:24:07,540
Remember, the winding isn't connected to the rest of the circuit.

185
00:24:09,440 --> 00:24:11,700
And here I set the frequency to 2 MHz.

186
00:24:11,800 --> 00:24:16,980
You see the ferrite handles 2 MHz pretty well.

187
00:24:16,980 --> 00:24:19,760
Now look at the rising edge.

188
00:24:21,040 --> 00:24:25,140
We have 10 ns per division.

189
00:24:25,380 --> 00:24:26,380
One division.

190
00:24:27,440 --> 00:24:33,420
Two divisions — 20 ns rising edge at 2 MHz.

191
00:24:34,700 --> 00:24:43,440
Now let's reconnect the winding to the circuit and see how it works with the subsequent chain.

192
00:24:46,440 --> 00:24:52,660
So, reconnected the secondary winding to the subsequent chain.

193
00:24:53,040 --> 00:24:58,780
Now we'll watch the signal that'll drive the power switch gate later.

194
00:24:59,620 --> 00:25:02,280
The probe will be at this point.

195
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:06,900
Oscilloscope common at this point.

196
00:25:07,560 --> 00:25:12,800
We'll watch the signal — connecting to the zeners.

197
00:25:12,800 --> 00:25:16,320
See the probe connected to the zeners.

198
00:25:16,740 --> 00:25:20,980
Switch to the oscilloscope screen.

199
00:25:22,060 --> 00:25:24,260
And start again at 1 kHz.

200
00:25:25,920 --> 00:25:29,240
There — a mess.

201
00:25:29,880 --> 00:25:31,440
How can you work with this?

202
00:25:32,140 --> 00:25:35,820
It's all related to the ferrite's frequency response.

203
00:25:39,920 --> 00:25:41,120
10 kHz.

204
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:46,500
The sweep is back to 5 V per division.

205
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:51,180
You see 10 kHz is too low.

206
00:25:51,680 --> 00:25:52,900
Switch to 20.

207
00:25:53,420 --> 00:26:04,220
And here you start seeing the signal take a fairly normal shape for driving the switch.

208
00:26:04,220 --> 00:26:08,960
At about 40 kHz and above.

209
00:26:09,840 --> 00:26:10,800
Now 50.

210
00:26:11,580 --> 00:26:15,700
Can drive the switch easily.

211
00:26:16,860 --> 00:26:26,220
In general, this circuit with this ferrite can drive well from 15 kHz on.

212
00:26:26,940 --> 00:26:29,260
So let's run through the frequencies quickly.

213
00:26:30,230 --> 00:26:37,400
You see the subsequent chain has already removed the negative half-period.

214
00:26:37,540 --> 00:26:40,620
It's only minus 1.4 V now.

215
00:26:41,700 --> 00:26:48,340
And the positive half-period amplitude is 10–13 V.

216
00:26:49,280 --> 00:26:50,750
And raise the frequency.

217
00:26:51,260 --> 00:26:52,380
100 kHz.

218
00:26:54,260 --> 00:26:54,860
300.

219
00:26:57,680 --> 00:27:04,100
I want to draw attention to what I said — at some frequencies the ferrite gives a spike.

220
00:27:04,720 --> 00:27:16,000
And this spike can be very big — but since there are zeners in the power switch gate circuit, these spikes get cut.

221
00:27:16,560 --> 00:27:23,180
And you see now the max amplitude is 15–16 V, where the zeners are working.

222
00:27:24,680 --> 00:27:27,160
500 kHz.

223
00:27:31,690 --> 00:27:33,550
1 MHz.

224
00:27:35,890 --> 00:27:37,130
Frequency.

225
00:27:38,510 --> 00:27:46,070
Observe — there's a small transient but it doesn't affect switch operation.

226
00:27:47,210 --> 00:27:50,230
And here I immediately set 2 MHz.

227
00:27:50,770 --> 00:27:51,470
Circuit.

228
00:27:52,470 --> 00:27:54,590
Now let's go higher.

229
00:27:55,450 --> 00:27:57,810
2.2 MHz.

230
00:27:59,260 --> 00:28:00,510
2.4 MHz.

231
00:28:01,230 --> 00:28:02,150
2.5 MHz.

232
00:28:02,910 --> 00:28:12,070
You see the rising edge and the signal amplitude have pretty good parameters.

233
00:28:12,070 --> 00:28:18,970
At 20 ns per division — one division of rise.

234
00:28:23,870 --> 00:28:28,070
Observe at 3 MHz.

235
00:28:29,190 --> 00:28:36,970
The circuit works, and it suits our solutions very well.

236
00:28:36,970 --> 00:28:40,330
And now I'll go back to a typical range.

237
00:28:40,510 --> 00:28:47,950
Around 1 MHz — let's check the duty cycle regulation.

238
00:28:48,550 --> 00:28:52,310
Now the signal duty cycle is 50%.

239
00:28:52,550 --> 00:28:54,010
I'll lower it.

240
00:28:54,510 --> 00:28:55,170
40%.

241
00:28:55,170 --> 00:28:56,850
30%.

242
00:28:56,850 --> 00:28:58,930
20%.

243
00:28:58,930 --> 00:29:00,270
10%.

244
00:29:01,390 --> 00:29:09,890
And now show, for example, 9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3.

245
00:29:11,170 --> 00:29:19,490
So duty cycle 3% at 1 MHz — what the lab signal generator can allow.

246
00:29:21,610 --> 00:29:23,730
We have this signal.

247
00:29:24,770 --> 00:29:27,030
20 ns per division.

248
00:29:27,830 --> 00:29:34,030
The rising edge is in the range of tens.

249
00:29:34,130 --> 00:29:35,070
Now 10 ns.

250
00:29:36,510 --> 00:29:38,750
Yeah, about 10–12 ns.

251
00:29:42,170 --> 00:29:46,430
And let's regulate duty cycle higher.

252
00:29:50,940 --> 00:29:54,720
Now set 90%.

253
00:29:55,260 --> 00:29:57,760
90% duty cycle.

254
00:29:57,760 --> 00:30:03,900
So practically the circuit is operational from 1% duty cycle to 90%.

255
00:30:08,340 --> 00:30:12,520
80, 70, 50, 40.

256
00:30:12,980 --> 00:30:21,920
So you see the isolation transformer behaves quite predictably and stably across the frequency range.

257
00:30:24,820 --> 00:30:30,340
Let's check duty cycle regulation at 2 MHz.

258
00:30:30,620 --> 00:30:32,620
Now watch — 50%.

259
00:30:32,620 --> 00:30:38,680
40, 30, 20, 10%.

260
00:30:42,350 --> 00:30:43,750
5%.

261
00:30:45,930 --> 00:30:48,290
And now we increase.

262
00:30:52,240 --> 00:30:55,860
60, 70, 80.

263
00:31:02,890 --> 00:31:16,650
You see that at 2 MHz with 80% duty cycle we already have signal distortion.

264
00:31:16,810 --> 00:31:20,070
Some frequency response is overlapping.

265
00:31:20,070 --> 00:31:22,930
The frequency range is pretty high.

266
00:31:23,030 --> 00:31:27,090
I think you'll appreciate this circuit in your work.

267
00:31:32,330 --> 00:31:37,750
So, I finished the build of the attachment for the lab signal generator.

268
00:31:38,390 --> 00:31:43,550
I added the graphic marking for the terminal block pinout.

269
00:31:44,730 --> 00:31:52,850
Connected the power supply and the BNC connector for the lab signal generator.

270
00:31:52,970 --> 00:31:56,870
This is what the build looks like from inside.

271
00:31:58,070 --> 00:32:01,970
The boards are fixed with screws.

272
00:32:03,150 --> 00:32:07,470
This board is fixed with two bolts, this one with one.

273
00:32:07,870 --> 00:32:11,310
And here we have the power switch leads.

274
00:32:12,390 --> 00:32:18,210
Drain output is red, source output is blue.

275
00:32:19,350 --> 00:32:29,670
Now I'll start the system up and see how it works on an ohmic active load.

276
00:32:33,380 --> 00:32:35,240
So, I assembled a test stand.

277
00:32:35,840 --> 00:32:38,600
Load will be a 200 W lamp.

278
00:32:39,600 --> 00:32:48,320
Power will be at its nominal voltage for the lamp — 220 V DC from a lab supply.

279
00:32:49,520 --> 00:32:55,000
I'll watch the oscillogram on the scope and control it with the signal generator.

280
00:32:55,560 --> 00:32:58,000
Now you see the jumper is set.

281
00:32:58,200 --> 00:33:04,480
This corresponds to a jumper between source and the minus of the supply.

282
00:33:05,040 --> 00:33:12,020
So the load is included on the drain of the power switch.

283
00:33:13,160 --> 00:33:16,140
Raise supply voltage to nominal.

284
00:33:21,610 --> 00:33:23,390
I won't ride it at low.

285
00:33:25,070 --> 00:33:29,770
Going straight to nominal 220 V.

286
00:33:30,390 --> 00:33:35,870
Duty cycle is 5%, frequency 100 kHz.

287
00:33:36,630 --> 00:33:37,990
It's working.

288
00:33:41,640 --> 00:33:45,140
Now I'll gradually raise the duty cycle in steps.

289
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:48,880
Watch the lamp.

290
00:33:55,760 --> 00:34:16,880
10%, 15%, 25%, 35%, 45%, 55%, 65%, 75%, 85% duty cycle.

291
00:34:16,880 --> 00:34:18,580
Now the same.

292
00:34:18,920 --> 00:34:23,340
We'll look at the oscillogram.

293
00:34:24,240 --> 00:34:28,360
Back to 5% duty cycle.

294
00:34:28,880 --> 00:34:34,700
I want to note that voltage-wise, looking at the output where our probe is.

295
00:34:35,140 --> 00:34:38,240
The probe is now on the transistor drain.

296
00:34:38,860 --> 00:34:42,580
And oscilloscope common is on the minus of the supply.

297
00:34:42,580 --> 00:34:51,580
By voltage we'll have an inverted signal relative to the controlling signal.

298
00:34:52,560 --> 00:35:00,940
So at minimum control duty cycle we'll have maximum voltage duty cycle at the output.

299
00:35:06,420 --> 00:35:24,680
10%, 15%, 25%, 35%, 45%, 55%, 65%, 75%, 85% duty cycle.

300
00:35:27,920 --> 00:35:40,740
With quality parts and assembly, the power switch barely heats up.

301
00:35:40,860 --> 00:35:45,640
Slightly above room temperature.

302
00:35:45,740 --> 00:35:49,840
About 30 degrees at this load.

303
00:35:49,840 --> 00:36:01,700
The circuit handles the nominal at 85% system consumption.

304
00:36:01,780 --> 00:36:08,280
So for tests of this circuit, plenty of headroom.

305
00:36:11,680 --> 00:36:19,460
Now switch duty cycle to 55% and sweep through frequencies.

306
00:36:20,940 --> 00:36:24,740
200 kHz, 300, 400, 500.

307
00:36:25,880 --> 00:36:28,840
You see the lamp glows.

308
00:36:33,550 --> 00:36:35,930
Say, test at MHz.

309
00:36:38,390 --> 00:36:43,410
Now switched to radio frequency already.

310
00:36:45,150 --> 00:36:51,610
Watch the signal at 1 MHz, 55% duty cycle.

311
00:36:54,290 --> 00:37:05,150
65, 75, 85% at MHz consumption.

312
00:37:13,480 --> 00:37:19,380
Next I want to recommend the YouTube channel of a guy who goes by Ruslan X.

313
00:37:20,220 --> 00:37:25,520
He runs quality experiments in alternative energy.

314
00:37:26,620 --> 00:37:28,660
I recommend everyone replicate them at home.

315
00:37:29,120 --> 00:37:31,180
You'll see lots of new things.

316
00:37:32,480 --> 00:37:36,300
And also visit the Zaryad forum.

317
00:37:37,300 --> 00:37:40,720
The thread "Ruslan Akulabukhov's BTG Generator."

318
00:37:41,240 --> 00:37:44,420
"Setup prototype BTG Akula 0083."

319
00:37:45,060 --> 00:37:49,600
Starting from page 161, read his posts.

320
00:37:49,680 --> 00:37:54,560
He recently registered there too, also under the nickname Ruslan X.

321
00:37:54,900 --> 00:37:57,800
And he also brings his videos there.

322
00:37:57,800 --> 00:38:00,960
Here's this video for Brovin.

323
00:38:02,020 --> 00:38:05,800
I'll embed my video.

324
00:38:06,780 --> 00:38:20,300
In it, Ruslan very clearly shows what happens when powering a Tesla coil in Kacher mode from a battery.

325
00:38:21,320 --> 00:38:27,260
And why with that hookup you can't connect measurement devices.

326
00:38:27,800 --> 00:38:30,580
Oscilloscope and so on.

327
00:38:31,520 --> 00:38:32,960
How you can lose them.

328
00:38:33,460 --> 00:38:42,040
This very much aligns with what I showed you — the attachment to the lab signal generator, its schematic.

329
00:38:42,620 --> 00:38:44,480
And why I'm making it.

330
00:38:46,700 --> 00:38:50,540
I recommend studying his videos carefully.

331
00:38:56,620 --> 00:38:59,780
Hello, dear Vladimir Ilyich Brovin.

332
00:39:00,730 --> 00:39:02,660
Well, and the rest.

333
00:39:02,840 --> 00:39:05,780
Now I'll demonstrate one thing.

334
00:39:06,540 --> 00:39:09,380
And then you decide for yourselves what your measurements are.

335
00:39:09,480 --> 00:39:10,720
Correct or incorrect.

336
00:39:11,440 --> 00:39:13,080
So, here's what we have.

337
00:39:13,360 --> 00:39:16,400
We have a Tesla — here it is.

338
00:39:19,700 --> 00:39:21,100
Your regular Kacher.

339
00:39:21,540 --> 00:39:22,360
Here's the Kacher.

340
00:39:22,880 --> 00:39:24,980
Kacher transistor 805.

341
00:39:25,560 --> 00:39:26,360
It's in there.

342
00:39:28,160 --> 00:39:32,640
This is a step-up voltage converter.

343
00:39:33,580 --> 00:39:36,860
2.5 amps up to 30 V.

344
00:39:36,980 --> 00:39:41,640
In this case, 25 V is set.

345
00:39:42,200 --> 00:39:44,760
So there's our power source.

346
00:39:45,040 --> 00:39:46,300
Here's the power source.

347
00:39:47,180 --> 00:39:48,760
And the battery.

348
00:39:49,640 --> 00:39:51,360
Now I'll show the difference.

349
00:39:52,010 --> 00:39:57,300
And you guys can figure out what's what.

350
00:39:57,760 --> 00:39:59,690
There's also an oscilloscope probe.

351
00:40:00,320 --> 00:40:00,580
Here it is.

352
00:40:00,920 --> 00:40:02,300
Won't be connected anywhere.

353
00:40:02,860 --> 00:40:08,360
I'll just bring this probe near the Kacher points.

354
00:40:11,140 --> 00:40:13,390
Well, let's try.

355
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:19,140
Connect the power source to the Kacher.

356
00:40:20,620 --> 00:40:25,320
At the 12 V I have set, no current is required.

357
00:40:26,940 --> 00:40:29,900
A little spark will pop up at the end here.

358
00:40:30,580 --> 00:40:30,960
Kacher.

359
00:40:31,300 --> 00:40:33,800
The transistor will switch to Kacher operating mode.

360
00:40:34,640 --> 00:40:35,520
And start running.

361
00:40:35,740 --> 00:40:40,940
You can clearly see the conversion goes from 12 to 25 V.

362
00:40:41,040 --> 00:40:43,980
And the Kacher will be running at 25 V.

363
00:40:44,780 --> 00:40:46,880
We're not using the battery yet.

364
00:40:46,880 --> 00:40:47,500
We've got this.

365
00:40:48,540 --> 00:40:51,360
This is a screwdriver for us.

366
00:40:52,900 --> 00:40:55,760
It'll serve as the indicator.

367
00:40:56,920 --> 00:40:58,700
You'll see for yourselves.

368
00:41:00,140 --> 00:41:01,240
Off we go.

369
00:41:02,320 --> 00:41:03,080
Add.

370
00:41:05,300 --> 00:41:06,620
You can see it there.

371
00:41:09,840 --> 00:41:12,160
Hear it — it started.

372
00:41:12,780 --> 00:41:14,960
Set at 12 V here.

373
00:41:15,180 --> 00:41:16,540
Hear it — the little spark is running.

374
00:41:16,880 --> 00:41:17,800
Here's the little spark.

375
00:41:18,740 --> 00:41:20,620
And here's our Kacher.

376
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:22,060
So I just now...

377
00:41:26,040 --> 00:41:28,220
Apparently the transistor cut out.

378
00:41:29,140 --> 00:41:29,720
Most likely.

379
00:41:29,880 --> 00:41:30,540
Or something else.

380
00:41:32,380 --> 00:41:33,180
There — works.

381
00:41:33,760 --> 00:41:35,020
See it, yes?

382
00:41:35,340 --> 00:41:36,100
All works.

383
00:41:37,480 --> 00:41:38,720
Move to the schematic.

384
00:41:38,900 --> 00:41:40,140
Approach the heat sink.

385
00:41:41,080 --> 00:41:42,180
See the heat sink.

386
00:41:42,760 --> 00:41:44,060
You can touch here.

387
00:41:44,060 --> 00:41:44,400
Here.

388
00:41:45,180 --> 00:41:48,610
We can touch any Kacher point with the screwdriver.

389
00:41:49,180 --> 00:41:53,740
And we don't see anything special.

390
00:41:54,340 --> 00:41:55,380
Great.

391
00:41:56,060 --> 00:41:57,180
Turn off the Kacher.

392
00:41:58,680 --> 00:42:10,490
And now I'll connect this same Kacher to an autonomous battery power source.

393
00:42:12,130 --> 00:42:14,830
This is for one-eyed Volodya.

394
00:42:15,430 --> 00:42:19,230
I want him to pay attention to this too.

395
00:42:19,370 --> 00:42:27,550
When he asks someone to do measurements on a working device for him.

396
00:42:28,250 --> 00:42:29,190
For the future.

397
00:42:30,010 --> 00:42:34,250
So he understands what's being talked about.

398
00:42:34,890 --> 00:42:36,510
Doing the switch now.

399
00:42:37,410 --> 00:42:38,770
Plus end.

400
00:42:39,770 --> 00:42:40,410
Connect.

401
00:42:44,860 --> 00:42:45,780
All set.

402
00:42:45,840 --> 00:42:46,840
Just need to turn it on.

403
00:42:48,630 --> 00:42:50,940
Take the little screwdriver in hand.

404
00:42:52,490 --> 00:42:53,960
Well, turn it on.

405
00:42:54,120 --> 00:42:55,720
12 V.

406
00:42:56,180 --> 00:43:00,500
We have a little spark.

407
00:43:01,800 --> 00:43:03,020
Kacher is running.

408
00:43:03,420 --> 00:43:04,440
Take the screwdriver.

409
00:43:05,340 --> 00:43:05,900
And see.

410
00:43:07,460 --> 00:43:09,640
Bring the screwdriver here.

411
00:43:10,280 --> 00:43:10,840
See.

412
00:43:12,200 --> 00:43:15,580
Take an oscilloscope probe — not connected anywhere.

413
00:43:15,820 --> 00:43:16,680
One little end.

414
00:43:17,760 --> 00:43:18,480
See.

415
00:43:20,020 --> 00:43:23,180
And now tell me, one-eyed Volodya.

416
00:43:23,740 --> 00:43:25,460
How are you going to measure?

417
00:43:26,780 --> 00:43:31,320
You want all this gear to go to the dump?

418
00:43:32,100 --> 00:43:33,800
From your measuring?

419
00:43:36,060 --> 00:43:37,820
Even this here.

420
00:43:38,500 --> 00:43:40,220
Things like this don't survive it.

421
00:43:41,900 --> 00:43:43,760
Thanks for watching.

422
00:43:48,450 --> 00:43:55,570
And in our free-energy community something interesting happened.

423
00:43:55,690 --> 00:43:59,450
I knew about it for a long time of course — about half a year.

424
00:44:00,330 --> 00:44:11,150
A guy still didn't agree with our well-known inventor Ruslan Kulabukhov.

425
00:44:12,290 --> 00:44:14,430
And decided to sue him.

426
00:44:15,810 --> 00:44:19,530
A comment came in on my channel.

427
00:44:20,150 --> 00:44:21,350
Now I'll show you.

428
00:44:21,530 --> 00:44:25,930
Here you can see all kinds of interesting comments showing up.

429
00:44:26,170 --> 00:44:28,550
The Kulabukhov setup turned out to be a fake.

430
00:44:29,330 --> 00:44:34,430
And here's a post from Sergey himself under the nickname Sergey Sergey.

431
00:44:35,570 --> 00:44:39,310
He gives a link to his video.

432
00:44:40,650 --> 00:44:42,310
Cross over to it.

433
00:44:45,430 --> 00:44:56,190
And in this video called "How my family was deceived" by a free energy device.

434
00:44:56,550 --> 00:45:02,770
He tells how he bought a non-working sample from Ruslan.

435
00:45:03,270 --> 00:45:06,930
The video is about 44 minutes long.

436
00:45:06,930 --> 00:45:15,310
Of course we can only sympathize with Sergey for being deceived.

437
00:45:16,570 --> 00:45:21,950
But I'd advise not to start a special hysteria about it.

438
00:45:22,610 --> 00:45:30,090
Because if one dishonest person decided to make money this way —

439
00:45:30,670 --> 00:45:33,830
that doesn't mean the technology doesn't exist.

440
00:45:33,830 --> 00:45:37,170
And it doesn't mean we should give up.

441
00:45:39,570 --> 00:45:43,890
Because working systems exist.

442
00:45:46,850 --> 00:45:51,130
And I'll tell you a bit about one point.

443
00:45:51,830 --> 00:45:58,950
People who reach out to me on Skype often ask how much output it gives.

444
00:45:58,950 --> 00:46:04,330
How much you can hang on it, can you buy one.

445
00:46:04,990 --> 00:46:06,170
Everything along those lines.

446
00:46:06,810 --> 00:46:08,670
Guys, I'll tell you this.

447
00:46:09,610 --> 00:46:12,130
Like a lot of others who reached out to me.

448
00:46:12,810 --> 00:46:15,850
I think people will back me up if anything.

449
00:46:17,110 --> 00:46:24,610
The internet has built up a kind of halo around this topic.

450
00:46:24,610 --> 00:46:28,890
That the technology exists, it's been working for ages.

451
00:46:29,170 --> 00:46:35,010
And only some ignorance is keeping it from being implemented in life.

452
00:46:35,570 --> 00:46:38,930
Actually, the technology really works.

453
00:46:39,150 --> 00:46:43,790
There are many directions for how to implement these devices.

454
00:46:44,890 --> 00:46:48,010
And they're implemented in different variants.

455
00:46:48,010 --> 00:46:55,390
But they all share one point — the technology is at its earliest stage.

456
00:46:55,930 --> 00:46:57,450
That is, the output is unstable.

457
00:46:57,910 --> 00:47:05,310
What you see on the internet in clips where lamps light up.

458
00:47:06,670 --> 00:47:08,410
Those are one-off launches.

459
00:47:09,190 --> 00:47:15,830
Before that, the author won't tell you he tuned the device for several hours.

460
00:47:15,830 --> 00:47:18,100
Before it successfully launched.

461
00:47:18,530 --> 00:47:22,850
After that he films it and posts it online.

462
00:47:22,970 --> 00:47:26,750
We look at it and think —

463
00:47:27,310 --> 00:47:31,770
just a little more and we'll start doing all this.

464
00:47:33,550 --> 00:47:35,650
I want to give some advice.

465
00:47:35,790 --> 00:47:43,710
Don't treat this as a magic box that can deliver electricity like a wall outlet.

466
00:47:43,710 --> 00:47:48,810
Treat it as research about the world around us.

467
00:47:49,370 --> 00:47:56,710
This is a hobby, scientific work, research.

468
00:47:57,890 --> 00:48:02,250
Fast results won't happen here.

469
00:48:03,690 --> 00:48:11,130
Personally I've worked in this direction for about 8.5 years.

470
00:48:11,470 --> 00:48:15,290
Soon it'll be 9 — I lost count, but a long time.

471
00:48:16,090 --> 00:48:18,690
To get some results.

472
00:48:19,690 --> 00:48:23,410
So you'll have to put in the work.

473
00:48:23,490 --> 00:48:25,050
And everyone will have to.

474
00:48:26,210 --> 00:48:32,230
And the main reason these devices aren't sold —

475
00:48:32,250 --> 00:48:38,270
is that there's no notorious conspiracy.

476
00:48:38,770 --> 00:48:41,250
You'll be able to sell them.

477
00:48:41,970 --> 00:48:44,150
It's risky enough business though.

478
00:48:44,850 --> 00:48:49,610
No one will stop you from selling a single unit.

479
00:48:50,270 --> 00:48:56,330
The pushback starts when you want to patent it and put it into production.

480
00:48:57,410 --> 00:48:58,090
Then yes.

481
00:48:58,590 --> 00:49:08,590
But making one for somebody, or heating your own house — if you don't draw attention to it.

482
00:49:09,750 --> 00:49:12,370
That's quite possible.

483
00:49:14,530 --> 00:49:25,410
And it turns out that at the moment these devices are very unstable.

484
00:49:25,410 --> 00:49:34,010
And that's exactly the reason we still can't buy them.

485
00:49:35,630 --> 00:49:50,590
There are objective reasons — say, a guy made the device while he was at his home, and moving it to another location requires retuning.

486
00:49:50,590 --> 00:50:00,670
I'd compare buying such a device to when you buy a satellite TV receiver.

487
00:50:01,110 --> 00:50:13,830
If you don't have the skills, you have to call a technician at the install location who'll tune the receiver and aim the dish at the satellite for you.

488
00:50:13,830 --> 00:50:15,990
That kind of thing.

489
00:50:16,350 --> 00:50:20,630
These are the objective reasons the devices aren't sold.

490
00:50:21,230 --> 00:50:24,570
You can't sell an unstable device right now.

491
00:50:24,710 --> 00:50:27,190
No one really needs it.

492
00:50:27,790 --> 00:50:33,030
Even if it starts up one time in five or ten — well, it started, and that's all.

493
00:50:33,570 --> 00:50:37,310
So work and keep working on this technology.

494
00:50:38,630 --> 00:50:41,630
I wish you persistence — don't lose heart.

495
00:50:41,630 --> 00:50:44,630
What's happening now is trivial.

496
00:50:45,310 --> 00:50:50,250
Big greetings to our great specialist Ruslan.

497
00:50:51,590 --> 00:50:59,670
Because beating his chest, shouting on every corner that he's the specialist — now it's clear why he did that.

498
00:51:00,430 --> 00:51:04,130
To create a movement around himself.

499
00:51:05,850 --> 00:51:14,330
And when that many people follow you, it of course creates a halo that you've got many things going on.

500
00:51:15,630 --> 00:51:19,670
And as we see, the guy went down the slippery slope of fraud.

501
00:51:21,510 --> 00:51:27,250
It's not for us to judge him — that's Sergey's call, and god will be his judge.

502
00:51:27,250 --> 00:51:29,710
And we keep going.

503
00:51:30,610 --> 00:51:37,410
And on that note, I wish everyone successful experiments and all the best.
